3. FOUNDATIONAL STANDARDS AND VOCABULARIES
------------------------------------------

• Dublin Core (DCMI Terms)
  Foundational lightweight vocabulary. 15 core elements + dozens of refinements
  (title, creator, subject, description, date, type, format, identifier, rights,
  abstract, provenance, spatial, temporal, etc.). RDF-native; usable everywhere.
  Still the cross-domain lingua franca.

• EXIF (Exchangeable Image File Format)
  Technical camera/sensor data (make/model, exposure, GPS, timestamps, etc.).
  Extremely reliable when present.

• IPTC Photo Metadata (Core + Extension) — current 2025.1
  Dominant professional/archival image standard. Administrative, descriptive,
  and rights fields (headline, caption, keywords, creator, copyright, locations,
  people, events, artwork/objects). Evolved from IPTC-IIM.

• XMP (Extensible Metadata Platform)
  Adobe’s XML framework. Carries Dublin Core + IPTC + EXIF + custom schemas
  inside almost any file type. Preferred modern rich container.

• Schema.org
  Web-oriented structured data (JSON-LD). Excellent for creative works, people,
  places, events, products.

Others: MODS/METS, PREMIS, EBUCore/PBCore, ISO 19115, custom domain ontologies.

Principle: Prefer established vocabularies + application profiles.
Invent new terms only when necessary; map them back to standards.

