13. RISKS, ETHICS, AND PHILOSOPHICAL NOTES
------------------------------------------

• Over-automation can erase nuance and create false certainty.
• Bias in data or prompts propagates into tags.
• Privacy: faces, locations, sensitive content.
• Rights: copyrighted or personal data extraction.
• Epistemic humility: good systems surface uncertainty and alternatives
  rather than hide them. Metadata should support multiple coherent readings
  when the evidence does (parallel truths).

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

14. SUMMARY PERSPECTIVE
-----------------------

Accurate automated tagging is not “just throw an LLM at it.”
It is an engineering + information-science discipline that rewards:

  • Layered hybrid designs
  • Standards literacy
  • Rigorous evaluation
  • Provenance-first thinking
  • Domain-specific craft

The highest-accuracy systems treat extraction as a knowledge production process.
They preserve evidence, confidence, and alternatives, and they keep humans
in the loop where judgment matters.

